msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:523
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:611
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:523
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Pennant's built-in `array` and `database` storage drivers know how to properly store scope identifiers for all PHP data types as well as Eloquent models. However, if your application utilizes a third-party Pennant driver, that driver may not know how to properly store an identifier for an Eloquent model or other custom types in your application."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:525
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:613
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:525
msgctxt "P"
msgid "In light of this, Pennant allows you to format scope values for storage by implementing the `FeatureScopeable` contract on the objects in your application that are used as Pennant scopes."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:527
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:615
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:527
msgctxt "P"
msgid "For example, imagine you are using two different feature drivers in a single application: the built-in `database` driver and a third-party \"Flag Rocket\" driver. The \"Flag Rocket\" driver does not know how to properly store an Eloquent model. Instead, it requires a `FlagRocketUser` instance. By implementing the `toFeatureIdentifier` defined by the `FeatureScopeable` contract, we can customize the storable scope value provided to each driver used by our application:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:529
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:617
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:529
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "<?php\n\n"
"namespace App\\Models;\n\n"
"use FlagRocket\\FlagRocketUser;\n"
"use Illuminate\\Database\\Eloquent\\Model;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Contracts\\FeatureScopeable;\n\n"
"class User extends Model implements FeatureScopeable\n"
"{\n"
"    /**\n"
"     * Cast the object to a feature scope identifier for the given driver.\n"
"     */\n"
"    public function toFeatureIdentifier(string $driver): mixed\n"
"    {\n"
"        return match($driver) {\n"
"            'database' => $this,\n"
"            'flag-rocket' => FlagRocketUser::fromId($this->flag_rocket_id),\n"
"        };\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:539
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "if (Feature::for($user->team)->active('billing-v2')) {\n"
"    return redirect('/billing/v2');\n"
"}\n\n"
"// ..."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:553
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:641
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:553
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"serializing-scope\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:554
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:642
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:554
msgctxt "H3"
msgid "Serializing Scope"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:556
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:644
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:556
msgctxt "P"
msgid "By default, Pennant will use a fully qualified class name when storing a feature associated with an Eloquent model. If you are already using an [Eloquent morph map](/docs/{{version}}/eloquent-relationships#custom-polymorphic-types), you may choose to have Pennant also use the morph map to decouple the stored feature from your application structure."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:558
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:646
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:558
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To achieve this, after defining your Eloquent morph map in a service provider, you may invoke the `Feature` facade's `useMorphMap` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:560
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:648
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:560
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Illuminate\\Database\\Eloquent\\Relations\\Relation;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"Relation::enforceMorphMap([\n"
"    'post' => 'App\\Models\\Post',\n"
"    'video' => 'App\\Models\\Video',\n"
"]);\n\n"
"Feature::useMorphMap();"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:572
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:660
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:572
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"rich-feature-values\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:573
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:661
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:573
msgctxt "H2"
msgid "Rich Feature Values"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:575
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:663
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:575
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Until now, we have primarily shown features as being in a binary state, meaning they are either \"active\" or \"inactive\", but Pennant also allows you to store rich values as well."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:577
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:665
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:577
msgctxt "P"
msgid "For example, imagine you are testing three new colors for the \"Buy now\" button of your application. Instead of returning `true` or `false` from the feature definition, you may instead return a string:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:579
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:667
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:579
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Illuminate\\Support\\Arr;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"Feature::define('purchase-button', fn (User $user) => Arr::random([\n"
"    'blue-sapphire',\n"
"    'seafoam-green',\n"
"    'tart-orange',\n"
"]));"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:590
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:678
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:590
msgctxt "P"
msgid "You may retrieve the value of the `purchase-button` feature using the `value` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:592
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:680
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:592
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "$color = Feature::value('purchase-button');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:596
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:684
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:596
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Pennant's included Blade directive also makes it easy to conditionally render content based on the current value of the feature:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:598
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:686
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:598
msgctxt "CODE: blade"
msgid "@feature('purchase-button', 'blue-sapphire')\n"
"    <!-- 'blue-sapphire' is active -->\n"
"@elsefeature('purchase-button', 'seafoam-green')\n"
"    <!-- 'seafoam-green' is active -->\n"
"@elsefeature('purchase-button', 'tart-orange')\n"
"    <!-- 'tart-orange' is active -->\n"
"@endfeature"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:608
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:697
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:608
msgctxt "P"
msgid "When using rich values, it is important to know that a feature is considered \"active\" when it has any value other than `false`."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:610
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:699
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:610
msgctxt "P"
msgid "When calling the [conditional `when`](#conditional-execution) method, the feature's rich value will be provided to the first closure:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:612
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:701
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:612
msgctxt "CODE"
msgid "Feature::when('purchase-button',\n"
"    fn ($color) => /* ... */,\n"
"    fn () => /* ... */,\n"
");"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:617
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:706
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:617
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Likewise, when calling the conditional `unless` method, the feature's rich value will be provided to the optional second closure:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:619
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:708
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:619
msgctxt "CODE"
msgid "Feature::unless('purchase-button',\n"
"    fn () => /* ... */,\n"
"    fn ($color) => /* ... */,\n"
");"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:624
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:713
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:624
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"retrieving-multiple-features\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:625
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:714
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:625
msgctxt "H2"
msgid "Retrieving Multiple Features"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:627
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:716
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:627
msgctxt "P"
msgid "The `values` method allows the retrieval of multiple features for a given scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:629
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:718
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:629
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::values(['billing-v2', 'purchase-button']);\n\n"
"// [\n"
"//     'billing-v2' => false,\n"
"//     'purchase-button' => 'blue-sapphire',\n"
"// ]"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:638
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:727
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:638
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Or, you may use the `all` method to retrieve the values of all defined features for a given scope:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:640
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:729
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:640
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::all();\n\n"
"// [\n"
"//     'billing-v2' => false,\n"
"//     'purchase-button' => 'blue-sapphire',\n"
"//     'site-redesign' => true,\n"
"// ]"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:650
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:739
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:650
msgctxt "P"
msgid "However, class based features are dynamically registered and are not known by Pennant until they are explicitly checked. This means your application's class based features may not appear in the results returned by the `all` method if they have not already been checked during the current request."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:652
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:741
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:652
msgctxt "P"
msgid "If you would like to ensure that feature classes are always included when using the `all` method, you may use Pennant's feature discovery capabilities. To get started, invoke the `discover` method in one of your application's service providers:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:654
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:743
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:654
msgctxt "CODE"
msgid "<?php\n\n"
"namespace App\\Providers;\n\n"
"use Illuminate\\Support\\ServiceProvider;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"class AppServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider\n"
"{\n"
"    /**\n"
"     * Bootstrap any application services.\n"
"     */\n"
"    public function boot(): void\n"
"    {\n"
"        Feature::discover();\n\n"
"        // ...\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:674
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:763
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:674
msgctxt "P"
msgid "The `discover` method will register all of the feature classes in your application's `app/Features` directory. The `all` method will now include these classes in its results, regardless of whether they have been checked during the current request:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:676
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:765
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:676
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::all();\n\n"
"// [\n"
"//     'App\\Features\\NewApi' => true,\n"
"//     'billing-v2' => false,\n"
"//     'purchase-button' => 'blue-sapphire',\n"
"//     'site-redesign' => true,\n"
"// ]"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:687
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:776
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:687
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"eager-loading\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:688
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:777
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:688
msgctxt "H2"
msgid "Eager Loading"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:690
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:779
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:690
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Although Pennant keeps an in-memory cache of all resolved features for a single request, it is still possible to encounter performance issues. To alleviate this, Pennant offers the ability to eager load feature values."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:692
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:781
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:692
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To illustrate this, imagine that we are checking if a feature is active within a loop:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:694
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:783
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:694
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"foreach ($users as $user) {\n"
"    if (Feature::for($user)->active('notifications-beta')) {\n"
"        $user->notify(new RegistrationSuccess);\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:704
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:793
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:704
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Assuming we are using the database driver, this code will execute a database query for every user in the loop - executing potentially hundreds of queries. However, using Pennant's `load` method, we can remove this potential performance bottleneck by eager loading the feature values for a collection of users or scopes:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:706
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:795
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:706
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::for($users)->load(['notifications-beta']);\n\n"
"foreach ($users as $user) {\n"
"    if (Feature::for($user)->active('notifications-beta')) {\n"
"        $user->notify(new RegistrationSuccess);\n"
"    }\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:716
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:805
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:716
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To load feature values only when they have not already been loaded, you may use the `loadMissing` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:718
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:807
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:718
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::for($users)->loadMissing([\n"
"    'new-api',\n"
"    'purchase-button',\n"
"    'notifications-beta',\n"
"]);"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:726
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:821
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:726
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"updating-values\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:727
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:822
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:727
msgctxt "H2"
msgid "Updating Values"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:729
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:824
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:729
msgctxt "P"
msgid "When a feature's value is resolved for the first time, the underlying driver will store the result in storage. This is often necessary to ensure a consistent experience for your users across requests. However, at times, you may want to manually update the feature's stored value."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:731
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:826
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:731
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To accomplish this, you may use the `activate` and `deactivate` methods to toggle a feature \"on\" or \"off\":"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:733
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:828
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:733
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"// Activate the feature for the default scope...\n"
"Feature::activate('new-api');\n\n"
"// Deactivate the feature for the given scope...\n"
"Feature::for($user->team)->deactivate('billing-v2');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:743
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:838
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:743
msgctxt "P"
msgid "It is also possible to manually set a rich value for a feature by providing a second argument to the `activate` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:745
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:840
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:745
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::activate('purchase-button', 'seafoam-green');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:749
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:844
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:749
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To instruct Pennant to forget the stored value for a feature, you may use the `forget` method. When the feature is checked again, Pennant will resolve the feature's value from its feature definition:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:751
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:846
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:751
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::forget('purchase-button');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:755
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:850
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:755
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"bulk-updates\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:756
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:851
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:756
msgctxt "H3"
msgid "Bulk Updates"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:758
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:853
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:758
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To update stored feature values in bulk, you may use the `activateForEveryone` and `deactivateForEveryone` methods."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:760
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:855
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:760
msgctxt "P"
msgid "For example, imagine you are now confident in the `new-api` feature's stability and have landed on the best `'purchase-button'` color for your checkout flow - you can update the stored value for all users accordingly:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:762
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:857
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:762
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"Feature::activateForEveryone('new-api');\n\n"
"Feature::activateForEveryone('purchase-button', 'seafoam-green');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:770
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:865
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:770
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Alternatively, you may deactivate the feature for all users:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:772
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:867
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:772
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::deactivateForEveryone('new-api');"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:776
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:872
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:776
msgctxt "P"
msgid "This will only update the resolved feature values that have been stored by Pennant's storage driver. You will also need to update the feature definition in your application."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:778
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:874
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:778
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"purging-features\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:779
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:875
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:779
msgctxt "H3"
msgid "Purging Features"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:781
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:877
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:781
msgctxt "P"
msgid "Sometimes, it can be useful to purge an entire feature from storage. This is typically necessary if you have removed the feature from your application or you have made adjustments to the feature's definition that you would like to rollout to all users."
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:783
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:879
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:783
msgctxt "P"
msgid "You may remove all stored values for a feature using the `purge` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:785
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:881
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:785
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "// Purging a single feature...\n"
"Feature::purge('new-api');\n\n"
"// Purging multiple features...\n"
"Feature::purge(['new-api', 'purchase-button']);"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:793
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:889
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:793
msgctxt "P"
msgid "If you would like to purge *all* features from storage, you may invoke the `purge` method without any arguments:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:795
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:891
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:795
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::purge();"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:799
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:895
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:799
msgctxt "P"
msgid "As it can be useful to purge features as part of your application's deployment pipeline, Pennant includes a `pennant:purge` Artisan command which will purge the provided features from storage:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:801
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:897
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:801
msgctxt "CODE: sh"
msgid "php artisan pennant:purge new-api\n\n"
"php artisan pennant:purge new-api purchase-button"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:807
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:903
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:807
msgctxt "P"
msgid "It is also possible to purge all features *except* those in a given feature list. For example, imagine you wanted to purge all features but keep the values for the \"new-api\" and \"purchase-button\" features in storage. To accomplish this, you can pass those feature names to the `--except` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:809
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:905
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:809
msgctxt "CODE: sh"
msgid "php artisan pennant:purge --except=new-api --except=purchase-button"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:813
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:909
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:813
msgctxt "P"
msgid "For convenience, the `pennant:purge` command also supports an `--except-registered` flag. This flag indicates that all features except those explicitly registered in a service provider should be purged:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:815
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:911
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:815
msgctxt "CODE: sh"
msgid "php artisan pennant:purge --except-registered"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:815
msgctxt "P"
msgid "You may load all defined features using the `loadAll` method:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:817
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "Feature::for($user)->loadAll();"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:819
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:915
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:819
#~ msgctxt "P"
#~ msgid "<a name=\"testing\"></a>"
#~ msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:820
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:916
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:820
msgctxt "H2"
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:822
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:918
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:822
msgctxt "P"
msgid "When testing code that interacts with feature flags, the easiest way to control the feature flag's returned value in your tests is to simply re-define the feature. For example, imagine you have the following feature defined in one of your application's service provider:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:824
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:920
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:824
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Illuminate\\Support\\Arr;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"Feature::define('purchase-button', fn () => Arr::random([\n"
"    'blue-sapphire',\n"
"    'seafoam-green',\n"
"    'tart-orange',\n"
"]));"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:835
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:931
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:835
msgctxt "P"
msgid "To modify the feature's returned value in your tests, you may re-define the feature at the beginning of the test. The following test will always pass, even though the `Arr::random()` implementation is still present in the service provider:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:837
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:943
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:847
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"public function test_it_can_control_feature_values()\n"
"{\n"
"    Feature::define('purchase-button', 'seafoam-green');\n\n"
"    $this->assertSame('seafoam-green', Feature::value('purchase-button'));\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:848
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:954
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:858
msgctxt "P"
msgid "The same approach may be used for class based features:"
msgstr ""

#: ./docs/10.x/pennant.md:850
#: ./docs/11.x/pennant.md:966
#: ./docs/master/pennant.md:870
msgctxt "CODE: php"
msgid "use App\\Features\\NewApi;\n"
"use Laravel\\Pennant\\Feature;\n\n"
"public function test_it_can_control_feature_values()\n"
"{\n"
"    Feature::define(NewApi::class, true);\n\n"
"    $this->assertTrue(Feature::value(NewApi::class));\n"
"}"
msgstr ""

